<div id="introduction">
	

	<h4>Introduction</h4>

  <p>Deosai is a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plateau">plataeu</a>, <em>one of the <span style ="color:blue">highest (2nd highest)</span> in the world, </em>located in Gilgit Baltistan, <strong>Northern Pakistan</strong>. It sits at an altitude of  4,114 metres (13,497 ft) above sea level and boasts an area of 3,000 kmÂ². 'Deo' means giant and 'Sai' means shadow, thus the name; The land of the giants. It has been believed for many hundreds of years that this place is haunted by giants. The place has an eerily deafening silence that when observed, can be unnerving and make you feel extremely lonely.  No civilisation has managed to make a settlement here as this is very difficult due to icy winds, thunderstorms, and the famous Deosai unpredictable weather. Sometimes it will be cloudy in summer or sometimes it will be snowing or it might be overcast, the weather here truly has a mind of its own. For 8 out of 12 months, Deosai is covered in snow and for the remaining 12 months, it is lush green. As a result of this, the area is still uninhabited even in this age. Though no one lives here, people apart from tourists do pass through here. Nomads have picked Deosai as their path of choice, for centuries they have passed through here with a herd. It's an area relatively unexplored by foreign tourists, so it is very much a <strong>hidden gem</strong> for tourists in that regard. Wildflowers bright in colour cover the landscape of Deosai and make the surroundings sradiate. It is home to the infamous brown bear and many other forms of wildlife.<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deosai_National_Park" target="_blank">(More info)</a></p>
  <br/>
